===Etymology===
Modern usage appears to originate with {{w|Jock Young}} in 1971<ref>{{cite-book|author=Jock Young|authorlink=Jock Young|title=The Drugtakers: The Social Meaning of Drug Use|publisher=Paladin|year=1971|pages=182, 197|isbn=9780261632288}}</ref> and {{w|Stanley Cohen}} in 1972.<ref name="Cohen">{{cite-book|author=Stanley Cohen|authorlink=Stanley Cohen|chapter=Introduction to the Third Edition|title=Folk Devils and Moral Panics: The Creation of the Mods and Rockers|edition=3rd|location=New York City|publisher=Routledge|year=1972|year_published=2010|page=XXXV|isbn=9780415267113|oclc=802879559|text=The term 'moral panic' was first used by Jock Young in 'The Role of the Police as Amplifiers of Deviancy, Negotiators of Reality and Translators of Fantasy', in S. Cohen (Ed.), ''Image of Deviance'' (Harmondsworth: Penguin, 1971), p. 37. We both probably picked it up from Marshall McLuhan's ''Understanding Media'', published in 1964.}}</ref> Cohen states that "[they] both probably picked it up from {{w|Marshall McLuhan}}'s ''Understanding Media''".<ref name="Cohen"/>

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A semi-[[spontaneous]] or [[media]]-[[generated]] [[mass]] [[movement]] based on the [[perception]] that an individual, group, community, or culture is dangerously [[deviant]] and poses a [[menace]] to society; a public [[outcry]].

